ear when people start to look into this a bit more.<br /><br />The NFS patches have been available for a long time, so stability should<br />be reasonable.  I'd be more than happy if people who are interested in<br />this would take a look (the /proc interfaces should be re-done to work<br />with the new proc code, for example - I was just too lazy to do it<br />myself). <br /><br />Performance with the new code can be noticeably better: it depends a bit<br />on what you do.  NFS write speed certainly went up a lot, and the<br />directory caching is much better too.  The kernel nfsd allows for faster<br />serving too (but you need to get the user-level tools from Olaf Kirch to<br />do kernel nfsd). <br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
